2.24  We recommended the following:
Ensure that RPCPPE as at December 31 of each year, be submitted to the Auditor concerned not later than January 31 of the following year;
The Accounting Office to identify the composition of the PPE items and adjust the Books of Accounts and Registries to effect the PPE capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00 as provided by COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022;
The Municipal Accountant to compute regularly, correctly and in a consistent manner the annual depreciation for all depreciable assets in accordance with Sections 66 and 67 of IPSAS 17;
The Municipal Accountant and Designated Supply Officer maintain Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively, for each group of PPEs and reconciliation between these two records shall be undertaken regularly;
The Municipal Accountant and Designated Supply Officer to comply with the reportorial guidelines for semi expendable properties prescribed in COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022;
The Designated Supply Officer ensure that each PPE item is properly tagged with a property sticker that displays the Property Number in the correct format, along with other necessary information as required under COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and
Take up adjusting entries to record the adjustments/corrections.

4.14   We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The Municipal Assessor to regularly provide the Municipal Treasurer’s Office with the updated assessment roll on or before December 31 of each year;
The Municipal Treasurer ensure that the total assessed value from which the RPT/SET receivables were based is reconciled with the assessment roll of the Municipal Assessor;
The Municipal Treasurer prepare Certified List of Taxpayers showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for Calendar Year 2025 and onwards and furnish the same to the Municipal Accountant for proper recording;
The Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer, trace the cause/s of the discrepancies noted and prepare the necessary adjusting entries, if warranted;
The Municipal Accountant to set-up at the beginning of the succeeding year the RPT and SET Receivables and corresponding Deferred RPT and SET Income based on the certified list from the Municipal Treasurer or the Municipal Assessor’s Report on Real Property Assessment in its absence; and
The Municipal Mayor require the concerned official/employee to include as part of their commitment/target in the Individual Performance Commitment and Review (IPCR), the submission of the required/needed reports and be rated accordingly.

5.12   We recommended the following:
The coordination between the Municipal Accountant and the designated General Services Officer towards the full implementation of the perpetual inventory method in the recording of all Inventory Accounts to ensure proper accounting and promote better control in the receipt and issuance of supplies and materials;
The Designated General Services Officer prepare Requisition and Issuance Slip (RIS) and Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) to effectively track the actual supplies on hand. The SSMI and RIS shall then be furnished to the Municipal Accountant for proper accounting treatment;
The concerned personnel conduct periodic physical inventory of supplies and materials which shall be reported in the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) and submitted to the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively; and
Based on the RPCI, the Municipal Accountant compute for the costs of the remaining Inventory using the Moving Average Method, which shall be reconciled with the balance of Inventory accounts in the financial statements.

6.37     We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management Council (LDRRMC) and the Office of the Municipal Accountant reconcile their respective records (Utilization Report, Notes to Financial Statements, and LDRRMFIP and submit revised/corrected copies to the Office of the Auditor;
The LDRRMC ensure that the LDRRMF be strictly utilized exclusively for expenditures related to disaster prevention and mitigation, preparedness, response and rehabilitation, and recovery only;
The Municipal Mayor require PNP personnel they provided with meal allowance to submit a certification from the PNP Accounting Office that no other allowances or travel claim were issued to them from the PNP’s budget during the cited event and submit the same to this office; and
The Municipal Accountant:
prepare Adjusting Journal Entries to include in the Trust Liabilities the unexpended balance from current year appropriation;
prepare Adjusting Journal Entries to correct the charging of the expenditures;
submit to this office copies of the corresponding Journal Entry Vouchers;
prepare and submit subsidiary ledgers for the Trust Fund – DRRM for CY 2024;
prepare and submit revised/corrected subsidiary ledgers from prior years’ as discussed from previous years’ Audit Observation Memorandum; and
henceforth make sure that all DVs charged to the LDRRMF have clear and complete supporting documents to prove propriety of charging.

8.9  The above deficiencies were discussed in the previous year’s audit observations but were noted in the current year’s transactions, thus, we reiterated the following recommendations and Management agreed that the Accountant:
Trace back prior years’ records and identify the employees with under or over-remittance. Accordingly, remit immediately the unremitted contributions/loan payments or require the employee/s to pay in cash in case of over refund;
Make certain that the amounts deducted from the Gross Pay reconcile with the amounts remitted as summarized in the Remittance List, which should always be attached to the Disbursement Voucher to be submitted for post-audit;
Regularly/monthly transfer cash from the MEED Funds to the General Fund the corresponding amounts deducted for HDMF PS contribution and loan amortizations from the MEEDO assigned personnel; and
Take up necessary adjusting entries to correct mispostings.

9.15  We recommended the following:
The MEED Officer to re-evaluate the operations of the Hostels/Dormitories, Slaughterhouse, Public Market, and Municipal Cemetery to ensure effectiveness and efficiency in its operations and to avoid continuous incurrence of net loss;
The MEED Officer to expand the target market of its hostel’s catering and accommodation services to include the general public, tourists, and nearby institutions through strategic marketing efforts, competitive pricing, and service improvements;
The MEED Officer to intensify its efforts to collect past due on stall market rentals and water works operations;
The Municipal Accountant to ensure petty cash transactions are duly supported with complete and valid supporting documents and observe proper usage of CENRR and RER, otherwise transactions will be suspended or disallowed in audit; and
The Municipal Accountant to maintain special accounts in the General Fund for each of the LEEs as required by the Section 313 of the Local Government Code and reiterated by Section 1.3.1 of the Manual on Setting Up and Operation of Local Economic Enterprises.

12.11 We recommended and Management agreed to require the Municipal Accountant to:
Trace back prior years’ payroll and submit schedule/summary to the Auditor’s Office with information on pay period, names of persons liable, the amount deducted, and ND No.;
Prepare and properly update subsidiary ledgers/schedules for each official/employee determined to be liable for the amount disallowed;
Ensure that disallowances and their settlements are properly monitored and reconciled with the SASDC; and
Ensure that reports and supporting documents submitted by the accountable officers are immediately recorded in the books of accounts and submitted to the Auditor within 10 days of the ensuing month.

Maintain and update the schedules and aging of APs regularly complete with necessary details on the accounts and to ensure that the schedules are submitted on time;

Record the 10% retention money from Contracts as Guaranty/Security Deposits Payable; and

Take up correcting entry to adjust the P0.445 million and record the same as Guaranty/Security Deposits Payable.

Record the liquidation of cash advances in accordance with the generally accepted accounting principles.  Record the liquidation up to the extent of cash advance and the excess as expense if reimbursement is requested;

Require the Accountable Officer/s who have existing under liquidation to immediately pay/refund the corresponding amount; and

Henceforth, demand from the Accountable Officer refund of the excess/unutilized potions of cash advance upon liquidation attaching the Official Receipt for the payment made.

The Municipal Accountant to ensure that all travel claims are duly supported by complete supporting documents as provided by pertinent laws and regulations and advise the officials and employees of the proper usage of CENRR and RER;

The Municipal Accountant to only allow transportation expense and daily travelling expense in accordance with E.O. 77, to avoid overspending and incurrence of excessive and unnecessary expenses;

The Municipal Accountant to carefully review the supporting documents pertaining to claims for transportation and travelling expenses incurred by COS and JO personnel and ensure that such are supported with the additional requirements prescribed in Item B.5 of COA Resolution No. 2021-044; and

The Management ensure that future disbursements for travel are in accordance with the prescribed rules and regulations, otherwise, the same will be suspended or disallowed in audit.

